6:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-12","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Rate Mechanics"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Both exchanges calculate funding rates using 8-hour intervals at 00:00, 08:00, and 16:00 UTC. Bybit uses a time-weighted average price (TWAP) methodology with mark price references, while Bitget employs index price calculations with premium/discount adjustments. Bybit's funding rates typically show lower volatility due to their established market depth, whereas Bitget's rates can spike higher during market stress due to lower overall liquidity. Both cap funding rates at ±2% per interval to prevent extreme scenarios."}]]}]
7:["$","$Lc",null,{"items":[{"question":"Which exchange offers better funding rate arbitrage opportunities?","answer":"Bybit typically provides more stable arbitrage opportunities due to deeper liquidity and tighter spreads. Bitget can offer higher funding rate premiums on newer tokens but with increased slippage risk during position entry and exit."},{"question":"How do the funding rate calculation methods differ between these exchanges?","answer":"Bybit uses mark price-based calculations with TWAP smoothing, while Bitget relies on index price methodology. This can create temporary discrepancies in funding rates for the same underlying asset, presenting short-term arbitrage windows."},{"question":"Which platform has lower total costs for perpetual futures trading?","answer":"Bybit has lower taker fees at 0.055% versus Bitget's 0.06%, saving 0.5 basis points per trade. For funding rate arbitrage requiring frequent position adjustments, this fee difference compounds significantly over time."},{"question":"Are there execution quality differences affecting arbitrage strategies?","answer":"Bybit's matching engine processes orders faster with better fill rates during volatile periods. Bitget's execution can lag during high-volume periods, potentially causing slippage that erodes funding rate arbitrage profits, especially in smaller cap perpetuals."}]}]
